        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText> 
The main goal of this science goal is to image the continuum which was detected to be ~95 mJy/beam with the SMA (1.5x1.0" resolution) in Vlemmings et al. (2011). 
As is the case for VY CMa (O'Gorman et al. 2015), the continuum of VX Sgr likely originates from more compact regions, conservatively estimated to be ~0.5" in size. With a 35 mas beam this implies a flux of ~0.5 mJy/beam. To confidently map the emission and potentially determine a spectral index throughout the band, we request at least a SNR of 20 and thus an rms of 25 microJy/beam.
The subsequent line sensitivity will allow us to also easily detect the SiO masers, and potentially even compact emission from the CO(2-1), the imaging of which can be done combining the low angular resolution science goal.

</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>
In order to optimize continuum sensitivity we place 4 1.875 GHz windows in the lower end of the band 6 receiver range. As at least three of these windows contain lines (SiO masers and CO) we maintain the same setting of the other Science goal (the low angular resolution setting) in order to optimally combine the data. The justification for this setup is repeated below:

The aim of the low resolution science goal is to
image the CO(2-1) emission around VX Sgr. We thus require
observations in band 6. The linewidth of ~30 km/s is easily
sufficient for the correlator  setting with the coarsest spectral
resolution (1.875~GHz total bandwidth,  dual polarization) with a
factor of two spectral averaging. In band 6 this setting
achieves approximately 1.5 km/s velocity resolution. The four
spectral windows were chosen to also maximize the continuum
sensitivity and cover the previously observed SiO(5-4) masers.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The scale of the dust emission is conservatively estimated to be ~0.5" or less. 
In order to relate the emission to the star and/or potential separated clumps we need to resolve at the order of 35 mas, which can just be reached with the longest ALMA baselines.
The largest angular scale almost matches the expected 0.5" extent, but any missing flux will easily be picked up with the lower-angular resolution second science goal of the proposal.

</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
