        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>
The JCMT observations presented in De Beck et al. (2010) indicate a median flux of ~17 Jy for CO(2-1). Assuming the flux is uniformly spread over the expected extent of the CO(2-1) region (~8.6") this corresponds to ~10 mJy/beam (for a beam of 0.2"). Since we will want to detect the outer extent of the envelope, we request a SNR of 5, or 2 mJy/beam rms in 2 channels=2.9 km/s (covering the line with 10 velocity elements).
 
This will also achieve a continuum sensitivity of ~35 microJy/beam, which will very easily detect the continuum which, assuming the SMA measured flux of ~95 mJy per 1x1.5" beam and spread over 0.5" dust features, is ~15 mJy/beam.

</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The aim of this science goal is to image the CO(2-1) emission around VX Sgr. We thus require observations in band 6. The linewidth of ~30 km/s is easily sufficient for the correlator  setting with the coarsest spectral resolution (1.875~GHz total bandwidth,  dual polarization) with a factor of two spectral averaging. In band 6 this setting achieves approximately 1.5 km/s velocity resolution. The four spectral windows were chosen to also maximize the continuum sensitivity and cover the previously observed SiO(5-4) masers.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>One of the goals of this proposal is to probe the shape of the outer regions of the CO envelope. The outer radius of the CO envelope was estimated to be 13.500AU from the models in De Beck et al. (2010). These models were based on their single dish CO(2-1), CO(3-2) and CO(4-3) observations. At a distance of 1.57 kpc (Chen et al. 2007) the CO(2-1) will extend over ~8.6". To both be able to map the CO(2-1) emission at a resolution sufficient to resolve changes at the scale of the water maser region (&lt;0.4") while recovering the full extent of the emission (~8.6"), we require 0.2" resolution and two ALMA configuration. This is confirmed using the CASA simulator.

NOTE: although the high angular resolution science goal is mainly aimed at resolving the dust, the current setup allows the data to be combined for even better angular resolution imaging of the CO.
</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
