    <prp:abstract>The detection of a large scale strong magnetic field around the red supergiant VX Sgr and the recent ALMA high spatial resolution observations of massive dust ejections around VY CMa highlight important unknowns in the supergiant mass loss mechanism.  By observing the extended molecular CO envelope of VX Sgr and comparing potential asymmetries with the observed magnetic field configuration it will be possible to confirm the theory that the magnetic field plays an important role in the stellar mass-loss mechanism. Additionally, by imaging the small scale dust emission, it will be possible to confirm if magnetic mass ejections could be the cause of massive, cool, dust clumps observed in the near stellar environment. Only ALMA can provide the resolution and sensitivity to perform such observations. 

The large scale CO observations constitute a resubmission of an accepted Cycle 2 filler proposal though now in CO(2-1) for combination with the high angular resolution observations.</prp:abstract>
